{
  "text": "The types of infiltrating cells are also important for the diagnosis of myocardial disease, especially myocarditis. For example, the presence of eosinophils indicates eosinophilic myocarditis, while the presence of lymphocytes indicates lymphocytic (or viral) myocarditis. The present report also demonstrated that various types of cells, including neutrophils, T-lymphocytes, macrophages, and B-lymphocytes infiltrated around the degenerative or necrotic myocytes. Previous studies indicated that inflammatory cell infiltration occurs in response to myocardial damage in patients with pheochromocytoma (7, [CITATION_1] . The presence of these findings in the present patient seems to be compatible with myocardial damage.",
